# Dependencies
node_modules/

# Next.js build output
.next/
/out/
tsconfig.tsbuildinfo

# Cloudflare
# NOTE: a `#` is only a comment at the START of a line. A trailing one is part of
# the pattern — which is how `/.wrangler/  # comment` silently ignored nothing.
#
# .wrangler holds the LOCAL R2 (Miniflare) state: the dev bucket, with couples'
# JSON and their photographs in it. It must never be committed.
/.wrangler/
# The built Worker — 74 MB, and regenerated by every build.
/.open-next/

# Secrets. `.dev.vars` is wrangler's local secret file; the rest are the usual
# suspects. Nothing here should ever reach a remote.
.env
.env.*
!.env.example
.dev.vars
.dev.vars.*
.cloudflare-credentials

# Editor / OS
.DS_Store

# Agent scratch
AGENTS.md
CLAUDE.md
skills/
skills-lock.json

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# DELIBERATELY NOT IGNORED — these were, and it was wrong:
#
#   scripts/         `npm run seed`, `npm run gc` and `npm run seed:remote` live
#                    here. The rule came from the template this was forked from
#                    and would have quietly dropped every operational script.
#
#   .node-version    Cloudflare's build runner defaults to an older Node than the
#                    one this is developed on. Pinning it is the only way the
#                    remote build matches the local one — so the file has to be
#                    committed, not ignored.
#
#   data/design/     The design templates. `npm run seed:remote` pushes these to
#                    R2; they are source, not build output.
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
